    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <h3>What is the best AI coding assistant in 2026?</h3>
    <p>There is no single best AI coding assistant for everyone. Cursor is the best overall AI IDE for most developers. Claude Code is best for complex, large-scale coding tasks requiring deep reasoning. GitHub Copilot is best for developers who want AI assistance within their existing IDE. Windsurf offers the best value with innovative Cascade flows at $15/month. The right choice depends on your workflow, budget, and the type of coding you do most often.</p>
    <h3>Is Cursor better than GitHub Copilot?</h3>
    <p>Cursor is more powerful as a standalone AI IDE with better codebase understanding, multi-file editing through Composer, and a more integrated AI experience. However, GitHub Copilot works within your existing editor (VS Code, JetBrains, Neovim) and costs less ($10/mo vs $20/mo). If you want the deepest AI integration, choose Cursor. If you want to keep your current setup, Copilot is the practical choice.</p>
    <h3>Is Claude Code better than Cursor for coding?</h3>
    <p>Claude Code excels at tasks requiring deep reasoning and large context windows (200K tokens). It is superior for analyzing entire codebases, performing large-scale refactoring, and handling complex multi-file architectural changes. Cursor is better for day-to-day coding speed, inline autocomplete, and the integrated IDE experience. Many developers use both: Cursor for everyday coding and Claude Code for heavy lifting.</p>
    <h3>Which AI coding assistant is best for beginners?</h3>
    <p>GitHub Copilot is the most beginner-friendly option. It works inside familiar editors like VS Code, requires minimal setup, and provides gentle inline suggestions that help beginners learn patterns without overwhelming them. Cursor is also beginner-friendly with its intuitive interface. Claude Code has a steeper learning curve due to its terminal-based interface. We recommend beginners start with Copilot or Cursor.</p>
    <h3>Are AI coding assistants worth paying for?</h3>
    <p>For most developers in 2026, yes. AI coding assistants consistently demonstrate 30-55% productivity improvements in controlled studies. Even the free tiers of Cursor, Copilot, and Windsurf provide meaningful value. At $10-20 per month, a paid subscription typically pays for itself within the first few hours of saved time. The key is choosing the tool that matches your workflow rather than expecting any single tool to replace programming skill entirely.</p>
    <h3>Can I use multiple AI coding assistants together?</h3>
    <p>Yes, and many professional developers do. A common stack in 2026 is GitHub Copilot or Cursor for everyday autocomplete and inline suggestions, plus Claude Code for deep codebase analysis and complex refactoring. Some developers add Windsurf for its Cascade debugging flows. These tools complement each other well because they optimize for different aspects of the development workflow.</p>
